questiontext.text:
Right-angled triangles

Look at Figure 1 which could, for example, be a profile of a hill with a constant gradient.

The two right-angled triangles \(AB_1C_1\) and \(A B_2C_2\) are similar (because the three angles of triangle \(AB_1C_1\) are equal to the equivalent 3 angles of triangle \(AB_2C_2\)). From the basic properties of similar triangles corresponding sides have the same ratio. Thus, for example,

\[\dfrac{B_1C_1}{AB_1}=\dfrac{B_2C_2}{AB_2} \qquad \text{and}\qquad \dfrac{AC_1}{AB_1}=\dfrac{AC_2}{AB_2} \qquad\qquad(1) \]

The values of the two ratios (1) will clearly depend on the angle \(A\) of inclination. These ratios are called the sine and cosine of the angle \(A,\) these being abbreviated to \(\sin A\) and \(\cos A.\)

Key Point

\(AC\) is the side adjacent to angle \(A.\)

\(BC\) is the side opposite to angle \(A.\)

\(AB\) is the hypotenuse of the triangle (the longest side).

Example

Referring again to the figure in the previous Key Point, write down the ratios which give \(\sin B\) and \(\cos B.\)

Solution

\( \sin B=\dfrac{AC}{AB} \quad \cos B=\dfrac{BC}{AB}.\)

Note that \(\sin B=\cos A=\cos (90^\circ-B)\) and \(\cos B=\sin A=\sin (90^\circ-B)\)

A third result of importance from the previous Figure is:

\( \qquad \dfrac{B_1C_1}{AC_1}=\dfrac{B_2C_2}{AC_2} \qquad\qquad\qquad (2)\)

These equal ratios are referred to as the tangent of the angle at \(A\), written \( \tan A.\)

Key Point

\[ \tan A=\frac{BC}{AC}=\frac{\text{length of opposite side}}{\text{length of adjacent side}} \]

For any right-angled triangle the values of sine, cosine and tangent are given in the next Key Point.

Key Point

We can write, therefore, for any right-angled triangle containing an angle \(\theta\) (not the right-angle)

\[ \sin\theta = \frac{\text{length of side opposite angle } \theta}{\text{length of hypotenuse}} = \dfrac{\text{Opp}}{\text{Hyp}} \]

\[ \cos\theta = \frac{\text{length of side adjacent to angle } \theta}{\text{length of hypotenuse}} = \dfrac{\text{Adj}}{\text{Hyp}} \]

\[ \tan\theta = \frac{\text{length of side opposite angle } \theta}{\text{length of side adjacent to angle} \theta} = \dfrac{\text{Opp}}{\text{Adj}} \]

These are sometimes memorised as \(SOH\), \(CAH\) and \(TOA\) respectively.

These three ratios are called trigonometric ratios.

Example

Write \(\tan\theta\) in terms of \(\sin\theta\) and \(\cos\theta.\)

Solution

\( \tan\theta = \dfrac{\text{Opp}}{\text{Adj}} = \dfrac{\text{Opp}}{\text{Adj}} \cdot \dfrac{\text{Hyp}}{\text{Hyp}} = \dfrac{\text{Opp}}{\text{Hyp}} \cdot \dfrac{\text{Hyp}}{\text{Adj}} = \dfrac{\text{Opp}}{\text{Hyp}} \Big/ \dfrac{\text{Adj}}{\text{Hyp}}\)

So, \(\tan\theta=\dfrac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta}.\)

Key Point

Pythagorasâ€™ Theorem

Example

Use the isosceles triangle in the following figure to obtain the sine, cosine and tangent of \(45^\circ.\)

Solution

By Pythagoras' theorem \( \quad (AB)^2=x^2+x^2=2x^2 \quad\) so \(\quad AB=x\sqrt{2}.\)

Hence:

\(\quad \sin45^\circ=\dfrac{BC}{AB} = \dfrac{x}{x\sqrt{2}} = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\)

\(\quad \cos 45^\circ = \dfrac{AC}{AB} =\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\)

\(\quad \tan 45^\circ=\dfrac{BC}{AC} = \dfrac{x}{x}=1 \)
